3. (3pt) What would be the accuracy of the naive model, such model that predicts every case to the majority category?¶

In a naive model, we give every diagnosis the value of 'B' because 'B' is the most prevalent out of the diagnosis types. This is obviously not accurate, because those with diagnosis 'M' aren't being showed. Hence in the naive model, we take all the values in the dataset that are actually diagnosed as 'B', and then divide it by the total number of those that are diagnosed as 'M' or 'B' (basically the whole dataset).

5. (7pt) Repeat all these steps with a few other sets of two features and a few other k-s of your choice.¶

In [16]:
#function that does everything
def metrics(x, metric, k):
    if(metric == "mahalanobis"):
        Sigma = np.cov(x, rowvar=False)
        m = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k,
            metric="mahalanobis",
            metric_params={"V":Sigma})
    else:
        m = KNeighborsClassifier(k, metric = metric)
    _ = m.fit(x,y)
    m.score(x,y)
    cv = cross_val_score(m, x, y, cv=10)
    print("k:",k)
    print("accuracy:" , np.mean(cv))
    ex1 = np.linspace(x1.min(), x1.max(), 100) # 30 elements 
    ex2 = np.linspace(x2.min(), x2.max(), 100)
    xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(ex1, ex2)
    # meshgrid creates two 30x30 matrices
    g = np.column_stack((xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()))
    # we create the design matrix by stacking the xx1, xx2
    # after unraveling those into columns
    # predict on the grid
    hatY = m.predict(g).reshape(100, 100)
    # imshow wants a matrix, so we reshape the predicted
    # vector into one
    _ = plt.imshow(hatY, extent=(x1.min(), x1.max(), x2.min(), x2.max()), aspect="auto", interpolation="none", origin="lower", alpha=0.3)
    _ = plt.scatter(x1, x2, c=y, edgecolor="k", s=8) 
    _ = plt.show()

6. (10pt) Describe your observations. How well do original/normalized/Mahalanobis-transformed features work? Does it depend on the features? Does the visual impression from images align with the cross-validation results?¶

Normalized features seems to match the graphs of the Mahalanobis-transformed features. I think the visual impressions align with the cv-results. Although the images look pretty similar to each other, you can see that the images of those with 89% accuracy are a little more precise than those with 87% (in terms of the background color). It seems like the lower the $k$ value, the higher the accuracy.

print(pixels.shape)
# convert the pixels matrix into Nx3 (or Nx4) matrix
# where N is the number of pixels, and 3 or 4 is the number
# of color channels
# so each row is a pixel, and the row data is its color value
M = pixels.reshape((-1,pixels.shape[2])) 
print(M.shape)

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
m = KMeans(16).fit(M) # cluster the color values
cl = m.predict(M) # find the cluster id for each pixel
centers = m.cluster_centers_ # find the cluster centers (i.e. colors) 
print("center color values:\n", centers)

compressed = centers[cl]/255 # normalize to between 0 and 1 
compressed = compressed.reshape(pixels.shape)
# make it back to NxM array
ax = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
ax.set_aspect("equal")
_ = plt.imshow(compressed) 
_ = plt.show()

2. (24pt) Get this code to work with your image and understand what it does. Explain:¶

(a) What does shape of pixels mean¶

Doing pixels.shape will give the size (i.e dimensions) of the picture. It gives the row, height, and color of the picture.

(b) What is matrix M? Why does it have 671040 rows and 3 columns in this example?¶

Matrix M includes the number of pixels and the number of color channels. In the example given, it just means that the pciture had a total of 671,040 pixels and 3 color channels

(c) What do cl values tell us? E.g. if cl[12345] = 2, what does it mean?¶

cl is the id for the corresponding cluster. cl[12345] = 2 would mean that cl at position 1234 has a cluster id of 2.

(d) What are the columns of “center color values” printed above? E.g. the first row, second column is value 163.37. What does that number mean?¶

The rows of the "center color values" represents the clusters and the columns represents the position the center is at. The first row with a secind column value of 163.37 woud mean that the very first cluster (i.e cluster 0) has a centroid that is located at a height of 163.37.

(e) How many “center color values” are there? Why do we have this number?¶

There are 48 center color values in this picture. This is means that there are 48 centetroids for each cluster.

def colors(n):
    m = KMeans(n).fit(M) # cluster the color values
    cl = m.predict(M) # find the cluster id for each pixel
    centers = m.cluster_centers_ # find the cluster centers (i.e. colors) 
    print("center color values:\n", centers)

    compressed = centers[cl]/255 # normalize to between 0 and 1 
    compressed = compressed.reshape(pixels.shape)
    # make it back to NxM array
    ax = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
    ax.set_aspect("equal")
    _ = plt.imshow(compressed) 
    _ = plt.show()
